-- Actelion, EDF, Fiat, KBC, Roche, Total: European Equity Preview
-- B y   T a r a   L a c h a p e l l e
-- 2010-10-10T22:01:00Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-10/actelion-edf-fiat-kbc-roche-total-european-equity-preview.html
The following companies’ share may
have unusual moves in  European  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The  Stoxx Europe 600 Index  fell less than 0.1 percent to
262.27. The  Stoxx 50 Index  slipped less than 0.1 percent to
2,515.24. The  Euro Stoxx 50 Index , a benchmark for nations using
the euro, declined 0.1 percent to 2,785.43.  Actelion Ltd.  (ATLN VX): The biggest Swiss biotechnology
company, which may be a buyout target, formed a committee of
board members to evaluate alternatives, according to a person
with first-hand knowledge of the matter. The shares rose 10
percent to 49.34 Swiss francs.  Alcatel-Lucent SA  (ALU FP): The French telecommunications
equipment company has no plans for further restructuring
measures, Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung said, citing Chief
Executive Officer Ben Verwaayen. The shares rose 2 cents, or 0.7
percent, to 2.55 euros.  Autogrill  SpA (AGL IM): The world’s biggest manager of
airport and highway restaurants sold its Alpha Flight Group Ltd.
unit to Dubai’s Dnata for 100 million pounds ($160 million).
Autogrill gained 0.27 percent to 9.20 euros.       Electricite de France SA  (EDF FP): Constellation Energy
Group Inc. pulled out of negotiations on a $7.5 billion loan
guarantee to build a nuclear reactor in Maryland with
Electricite de France, the world’s biggest operator of nuclear
reactors. EDF shares rose 30 cents, or 1 percent, to 31.64
percent.  Euro Disney SCA  (EDL FP): The theme-park operator will pay
back 25 percent of its 1.9 billion-euro ($2.7 billion) debt by
2013, the Sunday Telegraph said, citing an interview with Chief
Executive Officer Philippe Gas. The shares fell 1 cent, or 0.2
percent, to 4.14 euros.  Fiat SpA  (F IM): The Italian carmaker has no plans to list
Ferrari SpA, Ansa said, citing Chief Executive Officer  Sergio Marchionne . Fiat climbed 0.72 percent to 11.21 euros.  Hochtief AG  (HOT GY): The German builder’s management-board
members are entitled to 14.7 million euros in cash compensation
if the company is taken over, Bild reported, citing Hochtief’s
annual report. An ad-hoc committee of Hochtief’s supervisory
board will meet Oct. 11 to discuss strategy in the takeover
battle with  Actividades de Construccion y Servicios , spokeswoman
Jutta Hobbiebrunken said by phone. The shares rose 0.1 percent
to 63.75 euros.  KBC Groep NV  (KBC BB):  Apollo Global Management LLC , the
private-equity firm founded by  Leon Black , is bidding to buy
life insurance policies with a combined face value of $6 billion
from the Belgian bank. KBC fell 0.2 percent to 33.43 euros.  Roche Holding AG  (ROG VX): The Swiss drugmaker said its
two-drug treatment combining an anticancer agent with Herceptin,
the company’s $5.27-billion breast-cancer drug, was about as
effective as, and caused fewer side effects than, Herceptin with
chemotherapy. The shares were unchanged at 139.1 Swiss francs.  Stobart Group Ltd.  (STOB LN): The U.K. provider of road,
rail, sea and air freight services may take over Aer Arann, a
closely held Irish airline, the Sunday Business Post said,
without citing anyone. The shares fell 1 percent to 151 pence.  Swatch Group AG  (UHR VX): The watchmaker’s Chief Executive
Officer  Nick Hayek  said the strength of the Swiss franc won’t
prevent the company from reaching its target of 6 billion francs
($6.2 billion) in revenue this year. The shares fell 0.8 percent
to 361 francs.  Total SA  (FP FP): Europe’s biggest refiner began shutting
down its La Mede plant because of a lack of crude oil supply as
a strike by workers at the French port of Marseille’s oil
terminals continued. Total shares fell 5 cents, or 0.1 percent,
to 38.46 euros.  Vodafone Group Plc  (VOD LN): Vivendi SA and the world’s
largest mobile-phone company may put talks over the U.K.
company’s 44 percent stake in French mobile operator SFR on
their agenda in the coming months, the French weekly Journal des
Finances said, citing Vivendi Chief Executive Officer Jean-
Bernard Levy. The stock fell 0.3 percent to 161.2 pence.  Volkswagen AG  (VOW3 GY): Europe’s biggest carmaker will
expand vehicle and component production at its German factories
in Wolfsburg and Kassel, Stuttgarter Zeitung reported, without
citing anyone. The company’s preferred shares rose 2.5 percent
to 89.28 euros.  Wartsila Oyj  (WRT1V FH): The Finnish maker of ship engines
and power plants was cut to “sell” from “hold” at Deutsche
Bank AG by equity analyst  Timo Pirskanen . The 12-month price
estimate is 38 euros. The shares rose 1.2 percent to 48.49
euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
 Tara Lachapelle  in New York at 
